  "prompt": "How close are we to a real Iron Man suit?",
  "response": "While we're not quite at the level of Tony Stark's high-tech suit, significant progress has been made in various components:\n\n1. Exoskeletons\n- Military and medical researchers have developed powered exoskeletons\n- These can enhance strength and help people with mobility challenges\n- Examples include DARPA's TALOS project and medical rehabilitation suits\n\n2. Flight Technology\n- Jetpacks and personal flying devices exist\n- Companies like JetPack Aviation have created working jetpacks\n- However, they're not as controlled or compact as Iron Man's suit\n\n3. Protective Armor\n- Advanced body armor exists with ballistic protection\n- Some experimental suits offer limited powered movement\n- Materials science has improved protective capabilities\n\n4. Advanced Interfaces\n- Augmented reality (AR) helmets and heads-up displays are developing\n- Wearable computing is becoming more sophisticated\n\n5. Limitations\n- Current technology can't miniaturize power sources like the fictional arc reactor\n- Flight, precise maneuverability, and integrated weapon systems are still far off\n- Battery and energy storage technologies are major constraints\n\nWe're making progress, but a complete, functional Iron Man suit is still more science fiction than reality. Incremental advancements continue in materials, computing, and engineering.",
